title.narrative: OUTPUT 4.4 21ST CENTURY SKILLS

description.narrative: Output 4 (21st century skills): National and subnational governments have enhanced capacities to develop and implement a vision, plans, and strategies to equip adolescent girls and boys with 21st century skills they need for a positive transition to adulthood. , which contributes to Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: An increasing proportion of girls and boys, across the life cycle, especially the most disadvantaged, are learning in quality, safe and inclusive environments.

title.narrative: Output 4 (21st century skills): National and subnational governments have enhanced capacities to develop and implement a vision,plans, and strategies to equip adolescent girls and boys with 21st century skills they need for a positive transition to adulthood.

description.narrative: UNICEF supported MOECRT to scale up life skills education through an in-service online teacher training platform, reaching over 6,500 teachers (67% female). Further, more than 4,700 disadvantaged adolescents (58% girls) were supported to develop 21st century skills through an innovative 21st century skills digital learning programme, delivered in partnership with the private sector and subnational government partners. Good progress was also made under the reimagining education initiative, with a situational analysis of digital learning in Indonesia completed and a national symposium on digital education held, which identified gaps and opportunities for improving the quality and inclusiveness of digital education. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:03/12/2021
